[{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"EditURL = \"../tutorials/defective.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/#Defective-univariate-example","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"(Image: ) (Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"using LinearAlgebra\nusing TypedPolynomials\nusing MacaulayMatrix\nusing MultivariateMoments\nimport Clarabel","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"Consider the following system with a root of multiplicity 4:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"@polyvar x\nsystem = [(x - 4)^4]","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"The Macaulay framework finds the root with degree 4:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"solve_system(system, column_maxdegree = 4)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"Let's find the max rank PSD hankel from from the degree 4 Macaulay nullspace:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"ν = moment_matrix(system, Clarabel.Optimizer, 4)\nnothing #hide","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"We find the following PSD hankel","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"ν","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"Looking at its singular values, the rank seems to be 1:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"svd(value_matrix(ν)).S","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"The rank of the truncation is also 1:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"svd(value_matrix(truncate(ν, 1))).S","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"We conclude that the PSD hankel is flat. The root can be obtained using:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"atomic_measure(ν, FixedRank(1))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"The solution is also apparent from the equation in the nullspace of the moment matrix:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"nullspace(ν, ShiftNullspace(), FixedRank(1)).polynomials","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/defective/","page":"Defective univariate example","title":"Defective univariate example","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"EditURL = \"../tutorials/infinity.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/#Degree-gap-versus-staircase-gap","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"(Image: ) (Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"using TypedPolynomials\nusing SemialgebraicSets\nfunction system(k, solver)\n    @polyvar x y\n    return @set x == y^k && y^k == 0 solver\nend\nusing Random\nRandom.seed!(80)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"Let's start with the classical approach with all columns up to degree 5 and waiting for the gap:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"using MacaulayMatrix\nsys_gap = system(4, MacaulayMatrix.Solver(sparse_columns = false, wait_for_gap = true))\nsolutions = collect(sys_gap)\nnothing #hide","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We find the expected solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solutions","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"If we don't wait for the gap, we get it earlier:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"using MacaulayMatrix\nsys = system(4, MacaulayMatrix.Solver(sparse_columns = false))\nsolutions = collect(sys)\nnothing #hide","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We find the expected solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solutions","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"But we can actually also just use the 2 columns that are actually used:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"sys_sparse = system(4, MacaulayMatrix.Solver())\nsolutions = collect(sys_sparse)\nnothing #hide","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We find the expected solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solutions","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/#In-more-details","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"In more details","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solver_gap = init(sys_gap, sys_gap.solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"After one step, we don't have the solution yet","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"step!(solver_gap)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"After the second step, still no solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"step!(solver_gap)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"After the third step, still no solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"step!(solver_gap)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"After the fourth step, we find the solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"step!(solver_gap)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We can inspect the solver at follows","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solver_gap","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"The border dependence can be plotted for more visual inspection:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"using Plots\nplot(saturated_dependence(solver_gap))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We can see that the monomials of larger degree have not been used here. We can see them used with AnyDependence instead of StaircaseDependence","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solver_gap = init(sys_gap, MacaulayMatrix.Solver(dependence = MacaulayMatrix.MM.LinearDependence, sparse_columns = false, wait_for_gap = true))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"Let's solve again but not all the step at once:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solve!(solver_gap)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"This time, we see the monomials at infinity as the blue balls outside the staircase. We can see that the degree 4 contains no independent as it is the gap zone.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"using Plots\nplot(saturated_dependence(solver_gap))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/#Not-waiting-for-the-gap-in-more-details","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Not waiting for the gap in more details","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solver = init(sys, sys.solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"After one step, we find the solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"step!(solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We can inspect m for more details","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"solver","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"The border dependence can be plotted for more visual inspection:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"Even if there is no gap, the border is complete so we can get the multiplication matrices.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/#Sparse-columns-in-more-details","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Sparse columns in more details","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"sparse_solver = init(sys_sparse, sys_sparse.solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"After one step, we find the solution","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"step!(sparse_solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"We can inspect m for more details","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"sparse_solver","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"The border dependence can be plotted for more visual inspection:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(sparse_solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"As we can see, for the sparse one, the standard monomials are \"trivial\" because they are trivially detected as independent since they are not part of the basis. The border is missing but the multiplication matrix for y can be computed first and then, using this multiplication matrix, the missing relations for the border can be obtained and then the multiplication matrix for x can be obtained.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/infinity/","page":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","title":"Degree gap versus staircase gap","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"EditURL = \"../tutorials/dreesen2.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/#Getting-rid-of-root-at-infinity","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"(Image: ) (Image: ) Adapted from: Section~2.2.1 p. 33 of [D13]","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"[D13] Dreesen, Philippe. Back to the Roots: Polynomial System Solving Using Linear Algebra Ph.D. thesis (2013)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"using LinearAlgebra\nusing TypedPolynomials\nusing MacaulayMatrix\nusing JuMP\nusing MultivariateMoments","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Consider the system given in [D13, (2.3)] which corresponds to Systems/dreesen2 of macaulaylab:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"@polyvar x y z\nsystem = [\n    x^2 - x*y + z,\n    2y^3 - 2x*y^2 - 3x * y,\n    z^3 - x*y*z - 2,\n]","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We first try to solve the system:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"sols = solve_system(system, column_maxdegree = 6)\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"The real solutions are","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"sols","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/#Staicase-analysis","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Staicase analysis","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"solver = Iterator(system, MacaulayMatrix.Solver())\nstep!(solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can look at the solver as follows:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"solver","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can see in the border dependence that even if x^2 is a corner, the multiplication matrix for x cannot be computed as y^3 (resp. x*z^2, y*z^2) is standard but x * y^3 (resp. x^2 * z^2, x * y * z^2) is indepedent.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"using Plots\nplot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's do another step:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"This time, the blocker for computing the multiplication matrix for x are z^4 and y * z^3 among others.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's do another step:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Now they are z^5 and y * z^4 among others.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's do a last step:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Now we see that the whole border is dependent so the four multiplication matrices can be computed.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"In retrospect, we we probably should have expanded in priority towards larger exponents for z.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/#Saturation","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Saturation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's start again by starting with the same first stop.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"solver = Iterator(system, MacaulayMatrix.Solver())\nstep!(solver)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"This time, let's focus on saturating the first non-saturated standard monomials:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver, FirstStandardNonSaturated(10))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can see that z is now saturated:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's saturate the next one:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver, FirstStandardNonSaturated(10))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can see that y went from trivial to saturated:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's saturate the next one:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver, FirstStandardNonSaturated(10))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can see that x went from trivial to saturated:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"Let's saturate the next one:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"step!(solver, FirstStandardNonSaturated(10))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can see that z^2 is now saturated:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"plot(saturated_dependence(solver))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"We can see that this does not seem to work. By saturating a monomial, we generate all the rows that have a nonzero entry for the corresponding column in the MacaulayMatrix matrix. If the monomial is standard, it means that the column is a linear combination of other columns (which are dependent in the MacaulayMatrix Nullspace) of the MacaulayMatrix matrix. If we saturate these other columns, the linear combination may not work anymore. But we are only saturating the standard monomials, we don't saturate the rows that are dependent in the MacaulayMatrix Nullspace which explains the result we have seen here.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/#Moment-approach","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Moment approach","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"With moment matrix of degree 3:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"import Clarabel\nsolver = Clarabel.Optimizer\n\nM = moment_matrix(system, solver, 3)\nnothing # hide\n\natomic_measure(M, 1e-4, ShiftNullspace())","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"With moment matrix of degree 4:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"M = moment_matrix(system, solver, 4)\nnothing # hide\n\natomic_measure(M, 1e-4, ShiftNullspace())","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"With moment matrix of degree 5:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"M = moment_matrix(system, solver, 5)\nnothing # hide\n\natomic_measure(M, 1e-4, ShiftNullspace())","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen2/","page":"Getting rid of root at infinity","title":"Getting rid of root at infinity","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"EditURL = \"../tutorials/univariate.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/#Univariate","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"using LinearAlgebra\nusing DynamicPolynomials\nusing MultivariateMoments\nusing JuMP\nusing MacaulayMatrix","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"Consider the following example:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"@polyvar x\np = 3x^4 + 8x^3 - 6x^2 + 24x + 1\nq = differentiate(p, x)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"Let's solve that system:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"sols = solve_system([q], column_maxdegree = 4)\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"The real roots are:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"sols","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"With PSD Hankel matrix trick no complex root!","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"import SCS\nsolver = SCS.Optimizer\npsd_hankel([q], solver, 4)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"What happened there ? First, we computed the MacaulayMatrix matrix nullspace","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"Z = nullspace(macaulay([q], 4))","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"The PSD hankel matrix we find is:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"M = moment_matrix(Z, solver, 2)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"From which we get:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"atomic_measure(M, 1e-6)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/univariate/","page":"Univariate","title":"Univariate","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"CurrentModule = MacaulayMatrix","category":"page"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"Documentation for MacaulayMatrix.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"Modules = [MacaulayMatrix]","category":"page"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.Ellipsoid","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.Ellipsoid","text":"function Ellipsoid{T,M<:AbstractMatrix}\n    M::M\nend\n\nRepresent the set x'A'Ax = 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.FirstStandardNonSaturated","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.FirstStandardNonSaturated","text":"struct FirstStandardNonSaturated <: AbstractShiftsSelector\n    max_num::Int\nend\n\nSelect the first max_num standard monomials that are not saturated yet.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.ShiftStatus","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.ShiftStatus","text":"@enum(ShiftStatus, NOT_INCLUDED, INCLUDED, NOT_REDUNDANT, REDUNDANT)\n\nNOT_INCLUDED : Not included yet in the rows of the Macaulay matrix\nINCLUDED : Already included in the rows of the Macaulay matrix but redundancy unknown\nNOT_REDUNDANT : Already included in the rows of the Macaulay matrix and no redundancy with the other rows included\nREDUNDANT : Redundant with another row already included in the Macaulay matrix\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.add_monomial_ideal_generators!-Tuple{Any, MultivariateBases.MonomialBasis, Any, Any}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.add_monomial_ideal_generators!","text":"add_monomial_ideal_generators!(generators, standard_monomials, fixed, vars)\n\nGiven the standard monomials of a zero-dimensional monomial ideal, returns the generators of this monomial ideal of the form fixed * m where m is a monomial in vars and vars * m is not a multiple of any of the monomials in generators.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.cheat_nullspace-Tuple{MultivariateMoments.MomentMatrix, Vararg{Any}}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.cheat_nullspace","text":"cheat_nullspace(ν::MM.MomentMatrix, args...)\n\nReturn the nullspace of ν as matrix for each each row is an element of the nullspace.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.cheat_system-Tuple{MultivariateMoments.MomentMatrix, Vararg{Any}}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.cheat_system","text":"cheat_system(ν::MM.MomentMatrix, args...)\n\nReturn the nullspace of ν as an vector of polynomials.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.expand!-Tuple{LazyMatrix, Any}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.expand!","text":"expand!(M::LazyMatrix, degs; sparse_columns::Bool = true)\n\nAdd the row shifts for which the maxdegree of the shifted polynomial would be in degs. If sparse_columns is false then all monomials of degree in degs will be added to the columns. Otherwise, only the columns that correspond to the monomial of one of the shifted polynomials will be added.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.is_forever_trivial-Tuple{LazyMatrix, MultivariatePolynomials.AbstractMonomial}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.is_forever_trivial","text":"is_forever_trivial(M::LazyMatrix, col::MP.AbstractMonomial)\n\nReturn true if there does not exists any shift (even outside of M.row_shifts) that such that the shift of any of the polynomial has col as one of its monomial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.is_saturated-Tuple{LazyMatrix, MultivariatePolynomials.AbstractMonomial}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.is_saturated","text":"is_saturated(M::LazyMatrix, col::MP.AbstractMonomial; use_cache = true)\n\nReturn true if all possible shift of a polynomial such that col is one of the shifted monomial have been included.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.monomial_ideal_generators-Tuple{MultivariateBases.MonomialBasis}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.monomial_ideal_generators","text":"monomial_ideal_generators(standard_monomials)\n\nGiven the standard monomials of a zero-dimensional monomial ideal, returns the generators of this monomial ideal.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"Modules = [MacaulayMatrix.H2]","category":"page"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.F1-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.F1","text":"Second order H2 optimal approximation of linear dynamical systems, M.I. Ahmad, M. Frangos, I.M. Jaimoukha (2011) - Proc. of the 18th IFAC World Congress, Milano, Italy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.F2-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.F2","text":"Second order H2 optimal approximation of linear dynamical systems, M.I. Ahmad, M. Frangos, I.M. Jaimoukha (2011) - Proc. of the 18th IFAC World Congress, Milano, Italy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.F3-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.F3","text":"Second order H2 optimal approximation of linear dynamical systems, M.I. Ahmad, M. Frangos, I.M. Jaimoukha (2011) - Proc. of the 18th IFAC World Congress, Milano, Italy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.F6-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.F6","text":"Second order H2 optimal approximation of linear dynamical systems, M.I. Ahmad, M. Frangos, I.M. Jaimoukha (2011) - Proc. of the 18th IFAC World Congress, Milano, Italy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.FOM2-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.FOM2","text":"H2 Model Reduction for Large-Scale Linear Dynamical Systems, S. Gugercin, A.C. Antoulas, and C. Beattie (2008) - SIAM Journal on Matrix Analysis and Applications.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.FourDisk-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.FourDisk","text":"H2 model reduction for SISO systems, B. De Moor, P. Van Overschee, and G. Schelfout (1993) - Proc. of the 12th IFAC World Congress, Sydney, Australia.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.HomotopyH2_17-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.HomotopyH2_17","text":"Notes on computation time:\n\nq = 1-3 feasible (+-20 seconds).\nq = 2 : 500 paths\nq = 3 : 4 000 paths\nq = 4 : 33 000 paths (1 thread: ETA 3h)\nq = 5 : 164 000 paths (6 threads: ETA 4-5h)\n\nHomotopy methods for solving the optimal projection equations for the H2 reduced order model problem, D. Zigic, L.T. Watson, E.G. Collins, D.S. Bernstein (1992) - International Journal of Control.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.HomotopyH2_2-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.HomotopyH2_2","text":"# Solution from paper:\nA = -4998.078625\nB = 100.000194\nC = 100.000194\nprintln(\"Solution proposed in literature:\")\nprintln(ControlSystemsBase.tf(ControlSystemsBase.ss(A, B, C, 0)))\n\nHomotopy methods for solving the optimal projection equations for the H2 reduced order model problem, D. Zigic, L.T. Watson, E.G. Collins, D.S. Bernstein (1992) - International Journal of Control.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.Mauricio-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.Mauricio","text":"Globally Optimal H2-Norm Model Reduction: A Numerical Linear Algebra Approach, O.M.Agudelo, V. Christof, B. De Moor (2021) - IFAC-PapersOnLine.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.RationalL2_SISO-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.RationalL2_SISO","text":"Rational L_2 Approximation: A Non-Gradient Algorithm, A. Lepschy, G.A. Mian, G. Pinato, U. Viaro (1991) - Proc. of the 30th Conference on Decision and Control, Brighton, England.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.Spanos_1992_1-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.Spanos_1992_1","text":"A New Algorithm for L_2 Optimal Model Reduction, J.T. Spanos, M.H. Milman, D.L. Mingori (1992) - Automatica.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.Spanos_1992_3-Tuple{}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.Spanos_1992_3","text":"A New Algorithm for L_2 Optimal Model Reduction, J.T. Spanos, M.H. Milman, D.L. Mingori (1992) - Automatica.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.addPoly-Tuple{Vector, Vector}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.addPoly","text":"addPoly(x::Vector, y::Vector)\n\nReturn the coefficients (in decreasing power order) of the product of polynomials with coefficients x and y. (in decreasing power order).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MacaulayMatrix.H2.convolveSym-Tuple{Vector, Vector}","page":"Index","title":"MacaulayMatrix.H2.convolveSym","text":"convolveSym(x::Vector, y::Vector)\n\nReturn the coefficients (in decreasing power order) of the product of polynomials with coefficients x and y. (in decreasing power order).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"EditURL = \"../tutorials/dreesen10.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/#Positive-dimensional-roots-at-infinity","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"(Image: ) (Image: ) Adapted from: Example 6.14 p. 102 of [D13]","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"[D13] Dreesen, Philippe. Back to the Roots: Polynomial System Solving Using Linear Algebra Ph.D. thesis (2013)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"using LinearAlgebra\nusing TypedPolynomials\nusing MacaulayMatrix\nusing JuMP\nusing MultivariateMoments","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"Consider the system given in [D13, Example 6.14] which corresponds to Systems/dreesen10 of macaulaylab:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"@polyvar x[1:4]\nsystem = [\n    x[1] + x[2] - 1,\n    x[1] * x[3] + x[2] * x[4],\n    x[1] * x[3]^2 + x[2] * x[4]^2 - 2/3,\n    x[1] * x[3]^3 + x[2] * x[4]^3,\n]","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"With the classical MacaulayMatrix approach, the nullity increases by 2 at every degree because of the positive dimensional solution set at infinity.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"solve_system(system, column_maxdegree = 6)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"Let's compute the moment matrix of degree 4 from the nullspace of the Macaulay matrix of degree 5 using the Clarabel SDP solver:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"import Clarabel\nν = moment_matrix(system, Clarabel.Optimizer, 5)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"The nullspace of this moment matrix is a Macaulay matrix","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"M = nullspace(ν, ShiftNullspace())","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"Each coefficient is close to a rational number, after some clean up, we get the following system:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"real_system = clean(M; tol = 1e-6).polynomials","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"We have the equations 2x[1] = 1 and 2x[2] = 1 from which we get x[1] = 1/2 and x[2] = 1/2. We then have the equations x[3] = -x[4] and 3x[3] * x[4] = -2 from which we get x[3] = ±√(2/3) and x[4] = ∓√(2/3). Notice that the complex solutions are not solutions of the system anymore. The Macaulay solver indeed find these real solutions direction at degree 2.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"solve_system(real_system, column_maxdegree = 2)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/dreesen10/","page":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","title":"Positive dimensional roots at infinity","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"}]
